    m_PersistentCalls:
      m_Calls: []
  m_text: "Name:\n\nBenin Bronze Head (also called Benin Head, Ife/Bini Brass Head,
    or part of the Benin Bronzes)\n\nOrigin:\n\nBenin Kingdom, present-day Edo State,
    Nigeria\n\nDate:\n\nMost bronze heads date between the 13th and 16th centuries,
    during the height of the Benin Kingdom.\n\nMaterial:\n\nCast bronze or brass\n\nMade
    using the lost-wax casting technique, one of the most advanced metalworking methods
    of the pre-colonial world.\n\nPurpose / Significance:\n\nThese heads were created
    to honor Obas (kings) and important royal ancestors.\n\nThey were placed on altars
    during ceremonies to connect the living king with past rulers.\n\nThey symbolized
    royalty, spiritual power, continuity, and ancestral guidance.\n\nArtistic Importance:\n\nKnown
    for their realism, detail, and mastery in metal casting.\n\nConsidered among
    the greatest achievements of African art.\n\nThey demonstrate the high technological
    and artistic sophistication of the Benin Kingdom centuries before European contact.\n\nHistorical
    Context:\n\nIn 1897, many Benin bronzes\u2014including heads, plaques, and sculptures\u2014were
    looted by British forces during the punitive expedition.\n\nToday, they remain
    central to global debates on cultural restitution and museum ethics.\n\nSymbolic
    Features to Notice:\n\nHigh, patterned regalia or beaded crown\n\nFacial markings
    and stylized features\n\nNeck rings made from coral beads (symbols of status
    and power)\n\nCalm, composed expres"
