--- !u!114 &-5060555264820354465
MonoBehaviour:
  m_ObjectHideFlags: 0
  m_CorrespondingSourceObject: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabInstance: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabAsset: {fileID: 0}
  m_GameObject: {fileID: 1739407180364380487}
  m_Enabled: 1
  m_EditorHideFlags: 0
  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: 29b480dc3b7c34901916c4e135caebb1, type: 3}
  m_Name: 
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: Assembly-CSharp::ArtifactController
  artifactData:
    description: "Name:\n\nBenin Bronze Head (also called Benin Head, Ife/Bini Brass
      Head, or part of the Benin Bronzes)\n\nOrigin:\n\nBenin Kingdom, present-day
      Edo State, Nigeria\n\nDate:\n\nMost bronze heads date between the 13th and
      16th centuries, during the height of the Benin Kingdom.\n\nMaterial:\n\nCast
      bronze or brass\n\nMade using the lost-wax casting technique, one of the most
      advanced metalworking methods of the pre-colonial world.\n\nPurpose / Significance:\n\nThese
      heads were created to honor Obas (kings) and important royal ancestors.\n\nThey
      were placed on altars during ceremonies to connect the living king with past
      rulers.\n\nThey symbolized royalty, spiritual power, continuity, and ancestral
      guidance.\n\nArtistic Importance:\n\nKnown for their realism, detail, and mastery
      in metal casting.\n\nConsidered among the greatest achievements of African
      art.\n\nThey demonstrate the high technological and artistic sophistication
      of the Benin Kingdom centuries before European contact.\n\nHistorical Context:\n\nIn
      1897, many Benin bronzes\u2014including heads, plaques, and sculptures\u2014were
      looted by British forces during the punitive expedition.\n\nToday, they remain
      central to global debates on cultural restitution and museum ethics.\n\nSymbolic
      Features to Notice:\n\nHigh, patterned regalia or beaded crown\n\nFacial markings
      and stylized features\n\nNeck rings made from coral beads (symbols of status
      and power)\n\nCalm, composed expres"
